Now, foreign languages, as a subject, are held in the same way as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in independent school curricula and in other fields.
A 2014 survey by the British Commission on Employment and Skills found that for the reasons that employers gave for the struggle for the job, 17% were attributed to a lack of language skills.
As a result, more and more language skills are becoming imperative for preparing young people for their future career.
With multiple job opportunities that require foreign languages, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the career someone chooses, if they have learned a second language, they will have a real advantage in the future, having such a skill throughout their life.
The ability to communicate directly with people from foreign countries will automatically put a multilingual person before the competition.
According to a survey by YouGov of more than 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75% were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to carry a conversation, and French was the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage, 15%.
Therefore, investing in learning foreign languages is important for today’s children.
Having more languages, especially in developing countries, children will have a greater chance of finding meaningful jobs.
In Scotland, each school will teach other foreign languages.
A number of schools will focus on more modern classical languages, while others will learn languages that are considered to be most important to the UK when looking into perspective by 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child’s interest, there will always be several languages of choice within independent schools, with didactic frameworks that are specialized in this field.
Independent Scottish schools are dedicated to providing a learning environment that will prepare children and encourage them with the skills they need to succeed, whatever the future may be.
It cannot be denied at this time, in a global business environment, that languages continue to be vital to the country’s future, so it must be reflected in education.
Indeed, modern languages should indeed be considered "skills of international communication".
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
