Although Ri reiterated North Korea’s familiar objections to Washington’s opposition to a “staggered” approach to denuclearization, according to which North Korea would be rewarded if it took step-by-step, his statement seemed significant because it did not directly reject the denuclearization of the nuclear deal.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump during a premier summit between a U.S. president and North Korea's leader in Singapore on June 12, where Kim pledged to make progress towards a "denuclearization of the North Korean peninsula", while Trump was a North Korean.
North Korea sought an official end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States said Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
In addition, Washington has not given way to requests for relaxation of tough international sanctions imposed on North Korea.
“The United States insists on the option of ‘first denuclearization’ and increases pressure by sanctions to achieve its goal in a coercive way, even objecting to the ‘declaration of the end of the war’,” Ri said.
“The impression that sanctions can screw us up is an illusion that only people who don’t know us have.
But the problem is that the prolonged sanctions deepen our distrust.”
Ri did not mention plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump that the U.S. leader referred to at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister highlighted the three meetings between Kim and Moon Jae-in, South Korea’s president, over the past five months, adding: “If the issue of denuclearization had been negotiated with South Korea and not the US, denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not have been possible.”
Even under these conditions, Ri’s speech was very different from that of last year’s speech, when he told the UN General Assembly that it is inevitable to target U.S. territory with missiles from North Korea after “Mr. Evil President” Trump sent a “sync” to Kim.
This year at the United Nations, Trump, who threatened North Korea with “total destruction” last year, praised Kim for the courage to start the disarmament process, but said the work is just beginning and that sanctions will remain in place until North Korea is no longer in power.
On Wednesday, Trump said there is no planned period for this and added: “It doesn’t matter if it lasts two or three years or five months.”
China and Russia say Pyongyang should be rewarded by the UN Security Council for the measures taken.
However, U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the UN Security Council on Thursday: “The implementation of the Security Council’s sanctions must continue vigorously and uninterrupted until we achieve complete, final and confirmed denuclearization.”
The Security Council has unanimously increased the sanctions imposed on North Korea since 2006, in an attempt to block funds for Pyongyang’s nuclear and ballistic missiles programs.
Pompeo met with Ri on the colors of the UN General Assembly and later said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
