Harvard students take courses on how to get enough rest.
A new course from Harvard University this year encourages students to sleep longer, in an attempt to combat the growing “macho” culture that makes them subject to “all-night” energized, high-caffeinated learning sessions.
A scientist has found that, often, students of the world’s most prestigious universities do not even master the basic concepts of how they should take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, is the one who created the course, which is believed to be the first of its kind in the United States.
It was inspired to create the course after holding a conference on the impact of lack of sleep on the ability to learn.
“In the end, a girl came up to me and said, ‘Why am I being told this just now, in the last year?’
She told me she had never been told about the importance of sleep, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, first introduced this year, explains to students the essential concepts of how good sleep habits help improve academic and athletic performance, as well as overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health services, said the university decided to introduce the course after discovering that students were seriously deprived of sleep during the week.
An hour-long course can involve a series of interactive tasks.
Within a section is presented the image of a homeroom, and students can click on coffee pots, curtains, sports pants and books to tell them what the effects of coffee and light are and how athletic performance is affected by sleep deprivation, but also about the importance of a sound program.
In another section, participants were told how long-term sleep deprivation may increase the risk of developing heart attacks, strokes, depression, and cancer.
A campus map, with interactive pictograms, encourages participants to think about their daily program.
“We know that we cannot change the behavior of our students instantly.
But we believe that they have the right to know, just as everyone has the right to know what the effects of smoking on health are,” added Professor Czeisler.
The culture that makes students proud that they’ve learned all night still exists, he says, adding that modern technology and the increasing pressure on students have turned sleep deprivation into a growing problem.
Sufficient sleep, of a good quality, should be a student’s “secret weapon” for combating stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said, even to avoid weight gain, because lack of sleep makes the brain think that the body is hungry, which makes them sleepy.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old student from California who studies chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler create the course after taking one of his first-year courses at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to promote a course for all students.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask all graduate students to complete a similar study program before enrolling in this institution where the competition is fierce.
Professor Czeisler advised students to program an alarm to know when it’s time to sleep, as well as for waking up hours, and to know what are the harmful effects of “blue light” emitted by electronic screens and LEDs, which can disturb circadian rhythm and cause sweating.
