And now, a page in our Almanac Sunday morning: September 30, 1882, 136 years ago (and the CONTINUOUS counting...), is the day on which, in Germany, the future physicist Johannes Wilhelm "Hans" Geiger was born.
Geiger developed a method for detecting and measuring radioactivity, an invention that eventually led to the creation of the device known as the Geiger counter.
An essential device for science since then, the Geiger counter has also become essential for pop culture, as happened in the film "The Bells of San Coronado" (1950), in which Roy Rogers and Dale Evans played cowboys with improbable inclinations.
The man: “What else is that?”
Rogers: “It’s a Geiger counter, used to locate radioactive minerals, like uranium.
