National Trust Spying on the Secret Life of Lilies
New research that is being carried out on a property in the Scottish Highlands wants to reveal how they use the environment to hunt their prey.
It is hoped that the findings will reveal new things about the behavior of these new flying mammals and will help future conservation activities.
The study conducted by scientists at the National Trust for Scotland will analyze common dwarf bats and pigment bats, as well as eardrums and water bats from the Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recording equipment will be placed in key locations around the property to track the activity of the lilies during the season.
The NHS team and volunteers will also conduct mobile studies using manual detectors.
The specialized audio analysis of all recordings will estimate the frequency of sounds made by bats and which species emit certain sounds.
There will also be a map of the habitat and a report, to create a detailed, scale-up picture of their behavior in the environment.
Rob Dewar, a nature conservation consultant for NTS, hopes the results will reveal which areas of habitat are most important for bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as lawn creation, and what is the best way to maintain forest pastures for bats and other associated species.
Populations of bats in Scotland and throughout the UK have declined considerably in the last century.
They are dangerous to the construction and development work that affects their nests, but also to the loss of habitat.
And wind turbines and public lighting are risks, just like mouse traps and some chemical treatments for building materials, but also domestic cat attacks.
In fact, Lilies are not blind.
However, due to the fact that they hunt at night, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use a sophisticated eco-location technique to accurately identify insects and obstacles on their flight path.
NTS, which is responsible for caring for more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important parks and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, is thinking very seriously about bats.
They have ten trained experts, who regularly conduct studies, control the nests, and sometimes carry out rescue missions.
The organization created Scotland's first and only bat reserve, on the Threave estate in Dumfries and Galloway, where eight out of ten species of bats are found in Scotland.
The manager of the estate, David Thompson, says that this is the ideal territory for bats.
“Here at Dreamave, the area is great for butterflies,” he says.
“We have old buildings, lots of old trees and a perfect habitat.
But there are a lot of things we don’t know about bats, so the work we do here and elsewhere will help us understand why they need to multiply.”
It underlines the importance of looking for bats before performing property maintenance work, as simply unintentionally destroying a maternal nest could kill up to 400 females and chickens, which can destroy the entire local population.
Lilies are protected, and killing, harassing or disturbing them, as well as destroying their nests, are prohibited actions.
Elisabeth Ferrell, a Scottish official at the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to help.
She said: “We still have a lot to learn about bats and we don’t know how populations evolve for many of our species.”
